      "content": "You're hitting on a very real issue, and yes, that's exactly what happens when bias creeps into the system. Judges often rely on these stereotypes because they are deeply ingrained societal assumptions, not objective legal facts. When they use neighborhood as a proxy, they are essentially applying a systemic prejudice that disproportionately affects certain groups. This reliance on socioeconomic markers over individual actions is a classic example of how bias masquerades as judicial wisdom.",
